From: Gilly <gilroyscott1970@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 8 May 2026 00:00:00 +1000
Subject: [PATCH v2] net: phy: fwnode_mdio: deassert PHY reset GPIOs before ID scan

fwnode_mdiobus_register_phy() reads PHY identifiers via get_phy_device()
-> get_phy_c45_ids() before any per-PHY reset GPIO declared in the
device tree (reset-gpios on the ethernet-phy@N node) is toggled. The
reset GPIO is only honoured later, when mdio_probe() calls
mdio_device_reset() after the phy_device has been registered and
matched against a driver.

This is invisible on cold boot because bootloaders typically leave
PHYs out of reset, so MDIO reads return valid IDs. The bug becomes
visible whenever the MDIO bus is re-registered with PHYs in the
asserted-reset state, e.g. after:

    rmmod some_dsa_driver    # mdio_remove() asserts reset on each PHY
    modprobe some_dsa_driver # MDIO scan reads 0x0000 -> wrong driver

The IDs read as 0 because the PHY is held in reset, and phylib falls
back to a generic driver (Generic Clause 22 / Generic Clause 45) that
cannot drive a vendor-specific PHY correctly. There is no recovery
without another module reload sequence.

Reported on Airoha AN7581 with Realtek RTL8261N PHYs, where it
prevents the Realtek driver from binding after a second mt7530_mmio
load. The same race applies generically to any PHY that has
reset-gpios declared and is held in reset between two MDIO bus
registrations.

Walk the reset-gpios property of each child fwnode in
fwnode_mdiobus_register_phy(), drive it deasserted, honour the
declared reset-deassert-us settle time, then release the GPIO so the
later mdio_probe() reset cycle can re-acquire it via the phy_device's
struct device.

The cost on cold boot is one GPIO request/release plus the deassert
delay per PHY (typically 100-200 ms total), one-time at bus
registration. Negligible for the affected platforms.

Signed-off-by: Gilly <gilroyscott1970@gmail.com>
---
--- a/drivers/net/mdio/fwnode_mdio.c
+++ b/drivers/net/mdio/fwnode_mdio.c
@@ -7,7 +7,9 @@
  */

 #include <linux/acpi.h>
+#include <linux/delay.h>
 #include <linux/dev_printk.h>
+#include <linux/gpio/consumer.h>
 #include <linux/fwnode_mdio.h>
 #include <linux/of.h>
 #include <linux/phy.h>
@@ -119,6 +121,32 @@ int fwnode_mdiobus_phy_device_register(struct mii_bus *mdio,
 }
 EXPORT_SYMBOL(fwnode_mdiobus_phy_device_register);

+/* Deassert any reset GPIO declared on the PHY's fwnode before reading
+ * the PHY identifier. By default the per-PHY reset is only honoured later
+ * inside mdio_probe() -> mdio_device_reset(), but get_phy_device() reads
+ * the IDs before the phy_device is even created. Pre-deassert here so the
+ * scan does not fall back to a generic driver when a previous bus
+ * registration left the PHY in reset.
+ */
+static void fwnode_mdiobus_phy_predeassert_reset(struct fwnode_handle *child)
+{
+	struct gpio_desc *gpiod;
+	u32 deassert_us;
+
+	gpiod = fwnode_gpiod_get_index(child, "reset", 0, GPIOD_OUT_LOW,
+				       "mdio-scan");
+	if (IS_ERR_OR_NULL(gpiod))
+		return;
+
+	if (fwnode_property_read_u32(child, "reset-deassert-us",
+				     &deassert_us) == 0 && deassert_us)
+		fsleep(deassert_us);
+
+	/* Release so mdio_probe() can re-acquire the line on the
+	 * phy_device's struct device for its own probe-time reset cycle. */
+	gpiod_put(gpiod);
+}
+
 int fwnode_mdiobus_register_phy(struct mii_bus *bus,
 				struct fwnode_handle *child, u32 addr)
 {
@@ -133,6 +161,8 @@ int fwnode_mdiobus_register_phy(struct mii_bus *bus,
 	if (IS_ERR(mii_ts))
 		return PTR_ERR(mii_ts);

+	fwnode_mdiobus_phy_predeassert_reset(child);
+
 	is_c45 = fwnode_device_is_compatible(child, "ethernet-phy-ieee802.3-c45");
 	if (is_c45 || fwnode_get_phy_id(child, &phy_id))
 		phy = get_phy_device(bus, addr, is_c45);
